<DOC><DOCNO> AP890427-0100 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 1107EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-Nuke-Sleeping     04-27 0199</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Nuke-Sleeping,0204</SECOND><HEAD>Peach Bottom Plant Restarts After Shutdown</HEAD><DATELINE>DELTA, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Peach Bottom nuclear plant restarted todayafter a costly, two-year shutdown ordered by regulators after theyfound operators sleeping on the job.   The federal Nuclear Regulatory Commission granted final approvalfor a restart of Unit 2 Wednesday night and the chain reactionbegan about 5:40 a.m., said Bill Jones, a spokesman for plantoperator and part-owner Philadelphia Electric Co.   Peach Bottom will operate at very low power for the next twoweeks while safety checks are made. If all goes well, the plantshould reach full power in 14 weeks, he said.   The plant has been closed since March 1987 when the NRC saidsleeping and inattention by 33 control room workers posed a safetythreat to the public.   Philadelphia Electric shook up its top management and had to paysome $250 million for plant modifications, replacement power andits share of a $125 million fine, the biggest in NRC history.   The fine also was shared by the plant's other three owners:Public Service Gas and Electric of Newark, N.J.; Atlantic ElectricCo. of Atlantic City, N.J.; and Delmarva Power and Light Co. ofWilmington, Del.</TEXT></DOC>